 Board of Trade,\nwill address the midwinter\nmeeting of the District Bankers j\nAssociation at the Mayflower\nHotel tomorrow night.\nPrank A. Ounther, associa\ntion president and executive\nvice president of the Security\nBank, said the speaker will re\nport on population trends and\ndevelopment In the Washington\narea.\nMore than 375 bank officers\nand directors are expected to\nattend the meeting and heads\nof other leading trade associa\ntions here have been Invited. A\n1 buffet supper will follow the\nmeeting. j\nKipiinger, Coyle\nModerators for\nOutlook Session\nAustin Kipiinger, executive\nvice president of the Washing\nton' Kipiinger Agency, and\nWilliam E. Coyle, director of\npromotion and public relations\nfor Stations WRC and WRC\nTV, will be moderators for the\nsixth annual business outlook\nconference at the Willard\nHotel January 28.\nSponsored by the Waahing\nton Board of Trade, the Ad\nvertising Club, the American\nMarketing Association and the\nSales Executives Club or Wash\nington, the conference will\ncenter much of its attention on\npopulation growth of the\nWashington Metropolitan area\nI\nCOMMODITY PRICES\nNEW YORK. Jan IT JR The A\u00bb-;\n\u2022ocjsiied Index of 3.\u00bb lmponat*-\n1 commodities declined thu week lor the\nt aecony Aticceame week\nKonlerrou* metal* hit a 1957-58 low\n1 The grata; and cotton segment s\u00bbi\n1 thf only other group to shorn a lot*\nNarruv.lv ahead were industrial*, food\nlivestock ana textile*\nJan l? Wa Ago Vr Ago\ntomtnoditte* 189.27 184\ntadw rial* 17. HM 178 41 209.27\nf Food 14197 14104 14-'l 05\nl itehtoek 19187 I9i\u00bbn? ITU 7%\nI Grain* A cotton 178 179 52 191\n1 Textile l td 88 l.lrt 4? 147 04\nNocfer metal I712l*17\u00abn\u00ab\u00bb 224 31\nJ Net 1957-58 taw\nDIVIDENDS\n\nNEW YORK Jaa IS -Jt DlTidrndi\njr.-fC\nP-- Bik of Pt\u00bb-\nRkte nod, rreord able\nRrauUr\nBarlru hi iSr Q l-.1l \u2022-\u2022-in\nOt Nortb R\u00bbr Q \u2022:-:i :i-i:\nMead Jnhi.Mm rule Q .'l-14 4-1\nt' ,nr Eruli b l ,c a 3-is\n